{{Infobox film | name = The Travelling Artist | image = Tacover.jpg | alt = The Travelling Artist | caption = Original Artwork from The Travelling Artist | director = Jez Blackmore {{Unbulleted list}} Richard Hulse | producer = Ben Rose | writer = Jenni Grant | starring = Holly- Marie Laurence {{Unbulleted list}} Simon Baker {{Unbulleted list}} Poppy Flanagan a{{Unbulleted list}} Martine Sherlock a{{Unbulleted list}} | music = Mark Rowlands | cinematography = Petros Gikas | editing = Nikoleta Leousi | studio = Salford Films | country = United Kingdom | language = English }}
'''''The Travelling Artist''''' is an art house production inspired by [[German Expressionism|German expressionism]] co-directed by Jez Blackmore and Richard Hulse from a screenplay by Jenni Grant.
== Plot ==
A dark fairytale combining the drama of modern horror with classic elements of Gothic imagery inspired by the German Expressionist films of the 1920s.
A young artist, Lucy Snow, struggles bravely to cope with more than one grief; the plight of her seriously ill mother, and her own faltering talents as a painter.
Her dreams become haunted by a shadowy figure, the mythical Travelling Artist. This lonely wanderer, it’s whispered, has roamed the world for over a century in pursuit of his creative visions. Can such a man exist? And if he does, will his powers be able to rescue Lucy from sadness and what form will salvation take?
== Cast ==
* Holly- Marie Laurence as Lucy Snow * Simon Baker as The Travelling Artist * Poppy Flanagan as Lucy's mother * Martine Sherlock as Eliza Rose
== Influences ==
''The Travelling Artist'' is a modern take on classic German expressionist films including ''[[The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari|The Cabinet of Doctor Caligari]]'' (1920), ''[[Metropolis (1927 film)|Metropolis]]'' (1927), and ''[[Nosferatu]]'' (1922).
